    • Method Detail

      • sortedContains

        public static <T> Predicate<T> sortedContains(SkippingIterator<T> theIterator)
        Deprecated. 
        Returns a predicate that returns true when the argument exists in the given iterator with the caveat that the predicate should be called in sorted order. If the predicate is called first with one element and then with another element that is smaller then the second call is guaranteed to return false regardless of the contents of the iterator.

      • sortedNotContains

        public static <T> Predicate<T> sortedNotContains(SkippingIterator<T> theIterator)
        Deprecated. 
        Returns a predicate that returns true when the argument exists in the given itertor with the caveat that the predicate should be called in sorted order. If the predicate is called first with one element and then with another element that is smaller then the second call is guaranteed to return false regardless of the contents of the iterator.

        NOTE: The predicate returned by this function behaves exactly as Predicates.not(sortedContains(theIterator)) but slightly more efficient.

      • iterateUntil

        public static <T> PeekingSkippingIterator<T> iterateUntil(PeekingSkippingIterator<T> theIterator,
                                          T theMax)
        Deprecated. 
        Returns the elements of theIterator that are less than the given theMax value. Iterating over the returned iterator will cause theIterator to advance as well. After the returned iterator is consumed, calling theIterator.next() will return a value that is greater than or equal theMax if there are any more elements left.

      • iterateUntil

        public static <T> PeekingSkippingIterator<T> iterateUntil(PeekingSkippingIterator<T> theIterator,
                                          Predicate<T> thePredicate)
        Deprecated. 
        Returns the elements of theIterator that come before the first element that satisfy thePredicate. Iterating over the returned iterator will cause theIterator to advance as well. The predicate will be false for all the elements of the returned iterator. After the returned iterator is consumed, calling theIterator.next() will return a value satisfy the predicate if there are any more elements left.

      • union

        public static <T> SkippingIterator<T> union(SkippingIterator<T> theIterator1,
                            SkippingIterator<T> theIterator2)
        Deprecated. 
        Returns a skipping iterator that is the union of two given iterators where both the base iterators comply with the given comparator. The base iterators may span overlapping ranges and contain common elements. The resulting iterator will return all elements in sorted order and skip base iterators as needed. The duplicate elements from both iterators will be returned only once.

      • union

        public static <T> SkippingIterator<T> union(SkippingIterator<T> theIterator1,
                            SkippingIterator<T> theIterator2,
                            com.complexible.common.base.BinaryFunction<T,T,T> theMergeFunc)
        Deprecated. 
        Returns a skipping iterator that is the union of two given iterators where both the base iterators comply with the given comparator and performs the given merge operation when an element exists in both base iterators. When a duplicate is found in both operators only the result of the merge function will be included in the resulting iterator.
